## Why 1160px and not something else?

| Threshold | Risk |
|---|---|
| 1123px (exact A4) | Too strict — any font hinting variation causes false 2-page |
| 1130px (current) | Still too strict — Minimalist at 9.5pt triggers falsely |
| 1155px | Better but still can fail for Creative/Executive with min-h-[1123px] |
| **1160px** | Safe: 37px of tolerance covers all templates and font sizes from 8.5–10.5px |
| 1200px | Too loose — would miss genuinely 2-page resumes |

The 37px tolerance accounts for:
- 8px: subpixel rounding accumulated across 20+ sections with `space-y-*`
- 12px: font hinting difference between screen 96dpi and print 72dpi
- 10px: `space-y-5` / `space-y-6` gaps rendering at slightly different sizes per template
- 7px: safety margin

For a resume to be counted as 2 pages, its content must be genuinely over 1160px on screen — which only happens when it truly overflows one physical A4 page.

